name: Hamilton Internet of Things Meetup
description:
Tiny network connected (and in the near future intelligent) devices are everywhere. And soon they will be monitoring, controlling and filtering everything. So I think its probably a good idea to understand how these IoT nodes work and what we can get them to do.  Remember: "There is no fate but what we make for ourselves."

We will have the usual discussions and presentations, but I want to do a couple things different. First, I want to have a show and tell so people can give very short demos and talks about what they are doing. There will also be a Q&A so people can get help, but I will also setup a slack channel so everyone can keep in touch and interact outside of the meetup.

Now this is gonna real different. I'm going to provide a "library" of hardware and components that members will be able to borrow to explore IoT, microcontrollers, and sensors.

There will be just two rules for Iot Club:

1) If you borrow something return it if your not actively using it.

2) If you application becomes permanent, buy your own gear and return the borrowed items.

name: CodeYourFuture Scotland - A coding school for refugees
description:
We are CodeYourFuture - a coding school for refugees that started in London and currently in the process of expanding to Scotland (http://codeyourfuture.co/). In London, we have a class that is following a six-months program learning web development with the aim of placing them in Tech jobs by the end of the course. The class is a mix of nationalities and backgrounds, divided equally between women and men, and even though most of them had zero-experience with programming when they started, they are already acquiring skills that could open up great opportunities for them. The idea was inspired by HackYourFuture, an similar initiative in Amsterdam where 50% of the students managed to get entry level jobs in software development.

We are now in the process of starting our first class in Scotland (Edinburgh and/or Glasgow), and we're looking for people to help with setting up the school.

At this stage, we're mainly looking for people to help reaching the communities of refugees in order to recruit our first group of students, and in the same time, we're looking for volunteers to help with teaching the class (HTML, CSS, JS, React and Node -we have an open-sourced syllabus!) as well as helping with the general admin task.

This meetup is a way to get more people who'd like to help, and we'll hopefully gather to discuss CYF's idea and what we've been doing in London, and what we want to achieve in Scotland.

Until our first meetup, please contact me (Mozafar) for more details at scotland@codeyourfuture.co.

You can also read more about us over here:
Wired: http://www.wired.co.uk/article/codeyourfuture-refugee-coding-school
NewsDeeply: https://www.newsdeeply.com/refugees/articles/2016/10/19/welcome-to-londons-refugee-coding-school
UNHCR: http://www.unhcr.org/news/stories/2017/1/586e420c7/volunteers-train-refugees-to-crack-into-london-tech-industry.html

hello@jslovers.com

http://goo.gl/forms/8dFONGTIRbkhETD93 

What is JSLovers? 

At JSLovers we follow the approach of "Talk Less and Code More" approach. 

It is a platform where you can attend sessions,meet and interact with tech fanatics like you and share your knowledge with them. It also gives you a chance to share your enthusiasm of front end developers in Front-end field and apprise yourself of latest developments in the field.

Who are the face of JSLovers?

Currently, there are two of us  running the show and give our best. We are looking for people who want to come forward and share knowledge with the community.


What we have done so far?

We have a strong community of 500+ JSLovers on meetup

On Facebook we have 1000+

On our Facebook page - https://www.facebook.com/javascriptlovers on we keep posting and sharing valuable information about the technologies, meetups, Sessions and also post questions related to the JavaScript/Angular/Node/HTML, etc.


We also have our website Jslovers.com , which we try to update on regular basis.

Are these are paid or free? 

We know people LOVE FREE things, but in this world there is nothing like "Free Lunches".

Depends. Few are free and few are paid. If you are serious learner you won't mind paying for the knowledgeable sessions.


What is in future?

Our community is evolving and adapting to latest innovations in technology and market demands. Join our Meetup Group and FB page to know the latest of the industry and sessions.

CODE OF CONDUCT

If we find someone abusing or disrespecting the organizers, speakers or audience. We hold the right to ask that person to leave the workshop & community. We won't think once before blocking that person. 

Happy learning!!

name: Hyperledger Boston
description:
Does The Hyperledger Project have the potential to become the engine behind most successful decentralized applications and organizations created in the next 25-50 years? Absolutely!

A much better question is how, and in what new ways, can we:

a) Build decentralized applications, organizations and APIs at 10x the speed at 1/10 the cost.

b) Build situational awareness in the local community.

I believe that the convergence of decentralized applications, decentralized organizations, artificial intelligence and IoT brings upon us the Great Displacement of the 21st century, where the majority of workforce will be left without “conventional” jobs, forced to learn new skills and professions.

Why?

Founders of this group believe that the Hyperledger Foundation will be the engine behind decentralization of the world, a massive economic change of the next 25-50 years.

So.... why don't we standardize and democratize the field with and around Hyperledger?

What?

We are a local micro community of those interested in advancing their knowledge of Hyperledger, its use cases and applications.

How?

Join our group for a regular dose of human interaction, conversations, smiles, food and drinks on all things Hyperledger:

• Use Cases

• Competitive analysis of Hyperledger startups (Distributed Apps from disruptive companies in specific vertical markets)

• How-To’s

• Interviews with individuals working at the edge of the Hyperledger project

• Reviews of tools, services and APIs offered by the Hyperledger ecosystem

• Best Practices in Application Architecture

• Do’s and Don’ts

• Application Templates

• Hackathons

• Security in the decentralized world - on the edge, on the node, in the cloud and in transit

• How others solve some of the hard problems that exist in the world using Hyperledger.

https://www.hyperledger.org

https://github.com/hyperledger

Join the movement. Let’s change the world. Because with Hyperledger we can.
